Handwritten Digit Recognition with ARDIS Data
Jinhyun Kwon
Summary
This project created classication models for the handwritten digit images of the ARDIS dataset, which is
publicly available on the ARDIS GitHub website (https://ardisdataset.github.io/ARDIS/). Specically, this
project focused on analysis of the 7,600 handwritten digit images taken from the ARDIS III dataset.
The images were processed in R using the magick package, attened into rows, and compiled into a single
dataframe to be exported as a CSV le. We created three datasets corresponding to images with three pixel
resolutions: 12x12, 20x20, and 32x32, denoted as img_12, img_20, and img_32. Dimensional reduction
was applied to the 32x32 image dataset with principal components analysis (PCA). The rst 286 principal
components, which explained 90% of the variance, were extracted and stored in a separate dataset.
For each dataset, logistic regression, K nearest neighbor, linear support vector machine, random forest, and
bootstrap aggregating models were trained and evaluated based on their test set misclassication rates. Grid
searching by cross-validation was used to tune each model; tuning was completed with the caret packages
train() function.
The best model for the img_12 dataset was the random forest model with 12 variables per tree; the test
error for this model was 0.0367. The random forest model was also the best model for the img_20 dataset,
giving a similar test error of 0.04. For the PCA data, the best model was the KNN model with K=1, which
produced a test error of 0.0467.
Our results show that models trained on the data containing the lowest resolution images, the img_12 dataset,
performed as well as or better than equivalent models trained on the img_20 and PCA data. This seems to
suggest that, for digit recognition, lowering the image resolution (to a certain degree) can boost computation
speed and eciency without signicant loss of information or accuracy.
1
Introduction
Perhaps one of the most familiar applications of machine learning is image recognition technology. Facial
recognition technology is an oft-cited, yet especially controversial, example of the most practical, powerful
applications of contemporary machine learning innovations. Computers have neither the eyes nor the complex
brain structures that humans use to look at and recognize objects; to computers, images are just large matrices
of numbers. Nevertheless, researchers have devised a miscellany of predictive techniques that, combined with
exponential improvements in computing technology, has achieved a striking level of precision in computer
vision.
This project explores an elementary implementation of computer image recognition: handwritten digit
identication. More specically, the interest of this project is to apply some more basic statistical learning
techniques to a handwritten historical digit data called ARDIS (Arkiv Digital Sweden). The ARDIS data is
composed of JPG images of Arabic numeral samples extracted from over 15,000 dierent nineteenth and
twentieth century Swedish church records; the records were maintained by a number of dierent priests, each
possessing his own calligraphic idiosyncrasies. The data itself was gathered by the Department of Computer
Science from the Blekinge Institute of Technology in Karlskrona, Sweden and remains publicly available in
several formats on the ARDIS Github website (https://ardisdataset.github.io/ARDIS/). The dataset that
this project analyzes is the ARDIS III dataset, which contains 7,600 handwritten digit images with minimal
background noise760 images per digit (0-9).
Image Processing
The ARDIS GitHub supplies four dierent datasets, three of which include the digit images in varying formats
and one of which contains pre-processed numeric data on the digit images. We decided that, for the purpose
of this project, the ARDIS III dataset comprised of individual digit images with minimal noise strikes an
optimal balance between convenience and complexitywhile we do not have to worry about cleaning up
the images or identifying strings of digits, we do have to format these raw images as a numeric matrix to
properly apply our classication methods. Processing these images ourselves also allowed us to consider how
recognition accuracy suers at the cost of computational ease aorded by decreased pixel resolution.
R, by no means the best program for handling images, nonetheless provides sucient support for basic
manipulation; the magick package, a wrapper of ImageMagick for R, includes the simple image reading,
rescaling, and recoloring functions that we required. We wrote two functions, convert_to_row() and
ardis_data(), that completed the entire process of reading, editing, and attening images into a single data
set.
The convert_to_row() function takes two parameters: img, an image object, and res, an integer representing
the image resolution. Given the resolution, this function re-scales the image, converts all the pixel colors
to either # or #000000 (white or black), changes those color values to 1 or 0, and nally collapses the
image matrix into a single row.
The ardis_data() function, given a 0-9 digit and resolution, applies the convert_to_row() function with
the specied resolution to the 760 images of the given digit and gathers them into a single data frame.
The full 7,600 row datasets were created by applying the ardis_data() function ten times, once for each
digit, and then exported as CSV les. In total, we made three datasets, img_12, img_20, and img_32,
containing raw numeric data of 12x12, 20x20, and 32x32 pixel images, respectively.
2
The images in Figure 1 (below) illustrate how the conversion alters the original handwritten digit image.
Changing the original color to black and white does not lead to much loss of information. For simple numbers
like 1, increasing the pixel resolution does not markedly improve the clarity of its features; there is not much
detail needed because the shape itself is just a straight line. For more complicated digits like 8, the extra
detail from increasing the resolution leads to a somewhat more marked improvement in their identiability.
Increasing the resolution from 12x12 to 20x20 is a more drastic change in the image than increasing from
20x20 to 32x32, which suggests that the models for the img_20 dataset probably perform about the same as
the models for the img_32 dataset. The handwritten digits are identiable to the untrained human eye at
even the lowest resolution; whether such distinctions can be made by a computer remains to be seen.
Figure 1:
An illustration of the image conversion done with magick. The images are, from left to right: the original
image, the 12x12 pixel image, the 20x20 pixel image, and the 32x32 pixel image.
3
Principal Component Analysis
The img_32 dataset is composed of the converted 32x32 digit images and thus contains 1,024 covariates for
7,600 observations. Though the dimensions of the data do not present any immediate issues, training models
and performing cross-validation would be overtly computationally expensive, at least for our technological
resources. We therefore performed dimensional reduction on img_32 and trained models on that data instead.
Principal components analysis (PCA) on the img_32 data enabled us to reduce the number of predictors
from 1,024 to 286, the number of principal components that explain about 90% of the predictor variance.
However, the data is still "heavy" in the sense that the 286 columns now contain a wider range of values than
just 0 or 1, as in the original converted pixel matrix.

Classication Models
Linear Support Vector Machines
To train the linear SVMs (support vector machines), we performed a grid search for the optimal cost values of
each image dataset. 5-fold cross-validation was applied to estimate the out-of-sample error, and training was
completed using the caret package. Since the response variable has 10 levels, caret automatically applies
the one-against-one approach for linear SVM classication. The img_12 and img_20 data contain only
binary variables, and the dimensionally reduced img_32 data just contains the rst 286 principal components,
so it was not necessary to re-scale the predictor columns before training the SVMs.

K-Nearest Neighbors
We performed another grid search to nd the optimal K values for the KNN modelsagain, using the caret
package. As with the linear SVMs, we do not need to worry about re-scaling the predictor columns for the
KNN models.
Interestingly, the optimal K for all our data was 1; the plots in Figure 6 show that the 5-fold cross-validation
error continues to increase as K increases for all three datasets.

Conclusion
The best models for each dataset are summarized in the following table.
Data Best Model Optimal Parameter(s) Test Error
img_12 Random Forest mtry=12 0.0367
img_20 Random Forest mtry=60 0.04
PCA KNN K=1 0.0467
Table 4: Summary of best models for each dataset
Surprisingly, the img_12 dataset resulted in the model with the lowest test misclassication rate of 0.0367;
the random forest models for the img_12 and img_20 datasets performed about the same on the test set.
Moreover, the best model trained on the PCA dataset, the most information-heavy dataset, had the highest
test error overall. The overall similarities in test set performance suggest that the increase in image resolution
does not noticeably improve the handwritten digit identiability.
We assume for the linear SVMs that the boundaries for the data points is best approximated as linear, but,
seeing as the linear SVMs resulted in the highest test error for all 3 datasets, such an assumption likely does
not hold. While a polynomial or radial basis may have performed better, those benets would be realized
only after a very long training period. We attempted to perform a grid search for a polynomial SVM t to
the img_12 but discovered that it would take hours just for our 144 dimension feature space, which did not
bode well for the higher dimensional, more complex img_20 and img_32 PCA datasets. Hence, we forewent
the more complex SVMs. Certainly, given a faster, multi-core computer processor that allows for parallel
processing across several cores, we would have trained and evaluated the test performance of SVMs with
nonlinear kernels.
As noted earlier, a peculiar feature of the KNN models was that, for all three of our datasets, the best model
was the single nearest neighbor model. This 1-NN model lies at one extreme of the bias-variance trade-o, and
we would typically surmise that such a model is grossly overt to the training data and would consequently
not give adequate test results. However, after examining the test errors, we found that the 1-NN consistently
outperformed the other KNN models. Hence, contrary to our intuition, the 1-NN model is the best KNN
model for our data.
The main issues encountered in the project were technical; as mentioned before, we were unable to perform
grid searches for polynomial or radial SVMs because the computations would take too long. The grid search
for the random forest models initially posed a similar challenge. With the caret packages train() function,
we rst applied the standard rf algorithm (from the randomForest package) but found that the time it
took to get the out-of-bag errors for each mtry values was too long. We then tried parRF method with
the train() function, but this alternative tting method did not drastically improve the computation time.
Finally, in our next attempt, the ranger algorithm generated the tuning results within an hour; it is for this
reason that we chose to use the ranger algorithm for all our random forest/bagging model tting.
The image processing, though at rst unfamiliar, was surprisingly simple; the magick package provided all
the basic functions we needed, and we simply had to loop through the images downloaded from the ARDIS
GitHub. This looping process required some minor string manipulation to read in the dierent image les,
but that manipulation was the extent of our issues with handling the raw digit images.

Appendix
R Code for Image Processing
Function to convert image to single row given image object and resolution value.
#parameters are img object (use image_read from 'magick')
convert_to_row <- function(img, res) {
img %>%
#re-scale image
image_scale(paste(res, "x", res, "!", sep = "")) %>%
#convert to black and white
image_convert(type = 'Bilevel') %>%
image_raster() %>%
#change black to 0 and black to 1
mutate(col = ifelse(col == "#ffffffff", 1, 0)) %>%
#collapse
pivot_wider(id_cols=c("x", "y"),
names_from = c("x", "y"),
values_from = "col") %>%
return()
}
Function to convert all 760 images of a given digit into a dataframe.
#parameters are digit (0-9) and resolution (any positive integer)
ardis_data <- function(digit, res) {
#create empty dataframe
img_df = as.data.frame(matrix(NA, 760, res^2))
#set names of columns
names(img_df) = names(
#use local image file location
image_read(paste("ardis_3",
digit,
"/1.jpg",
sep = "")) %>%
convert_to_row(res))
#loop through all images stored locally and convert_to_row
#then, add to dataframe
for(i in 1:760) {
img = image_read(paste("ardis_3",
digit,
"/",
i,
".jpg",
sep = ""))
img_df[i,] = convert_to_row(img, res)
}
#create response column, y (actual digit)
img_df = img_df %>%
mutate(y = digit)
return(img_df)
}
Loop through all digits 0-9 and combine into a single dataframe, img_data. Change res value to match
desired resolution (12, 20, and 32 already created).

img_data = ardis_data(0, res)
for(i in 1:9) {
img_data = rbind(img_data, ardis_data(i, res))
}

R Code for img_32 PCA and PCA Models
Principal component analysis of the img_32 data.
img.pca <- prcomp(img[,-1025])
#calculate percent variance explained
pV = img.pca$sdev^2/sum(img.pca$sdev^2)
#calculate PC at which cumulative % variance explained is 90%
at90 = which.min(abs(.9 - cumsum(pV)))
PCA plots
#% variance for each PC
ggplot() +
geom_line(aes(x = 1:1024, y = pV)) +
xlab("PC") +
ylab("% of Variance") +
ggtitle("PCA % Variance")
#cumulative % variance
ggplot() +
geom_line(aes(x = 1:1024, y = cumsum(pV))) +
geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 0.9), linetype = "dashed",
colour = "red") +
geom_vline(aes(xintercept = at90), linetype = "dashed",
colour = "red") +
xlab("PC") +
ylab("% of Variance") +
ggtitle("PCA Cumulative % Variance")
Create dataframe of rst 286 PCs
